<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-03-10T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-03-10T13:00:00-05:00" n="602" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d602">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">865.4016/155: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Phillips</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-03-10T19:00:00+01:00">March 10, 1939—7
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received March 10—2:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>83. My 81, March 10, 10 a.m.<note n="50" xml:id="d602fn50">Not
                                    printed.</note> Ciano confirmed to me this afternoon the
                                information contained in my 78, March 8, 1 p.m. with regard <pb facs="0662" n="654" xml:id="pg_654"/> to foreign Jews in Italy.
                                Furthermore, he said that this applied also to the German refugees.
                                There will be no roundup or imprisonment of any foreign Jews in
                                Italy on March 12.</p>
                            <p>He gave me very definitely the impression that the decision had been
                                reached to relax the anti-Jewish campaign.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>